&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: Yeah.

00:05:07.500 --> 00:05:08.849
Hi, Jen.

00:05:08.849 --> 00:05:11.350
But we are, but yeah.

00:05:11.350 --> 00:05:12.350
I mean, I grew up.

00:05:12.350 --> 00:05:13.620
My dad was in the music business.

00:05:13.620 --> 00:05:18.410
And I grew up literally on the corner.

00:05:18.410 --> 00:05:22.420
His office was at 92 hundred Sunset, which
is like Doheny, and it's the beginning of

00:05:22.420 --> 00:05:23.420
The Strip.

00:05:23.420 --> 00:05:29.030
And my first concert that I went to, when
I was 12 years old, was at The Roxy, but it

00:05:29.030 --> 00:05:30.660
was The Cramps.

00:05:30.660 --> 00:05:38.490
And the lead singer pleasured himself and
finished on stage at the concert.

00:05:38.490 --> 00:05:39.590
And I was like, "Wow.

00:05:39.590 --> 00:05:40.590
Music is weird."

00:05:40.590 --> 00:05:41.590
[laughter]

00:05:41.590 --> 00:05:43.450
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: He fulfilled his contract.

00:05:43.450 --> 00:05:45.100
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: Yeah, exactly.

00:05:45.100 --> 00:05:49.340
But then, I was a huge Foreigner fan and a
huge Journey fan.

00:05:49.340 --> 00:05:50.340
And I started going to--.

00:05:50.340 --> 00:05:53.550
My first concert was actually David Bowie
at an arena.

00:05:53.550 --> 00:05:57.139
But anyway, so this was kind of my time.

00:05:57.139 --> 00:06:04.670
And what I remember about this time was that
it was the last period of our innocence, kind

00:06:04.670 --> 00:06:10.349
of, because these people were running amok
like children and there seemed to be no consequences

00:06:10.349 --> 00:06:11.509
for anything.

00:06:11.509 --> 00:06:16.639
You would just throw a couch out of a hotel
window and it was like, "Yaaaah."

00:06:16.639 --> 00:06:19.770
And you could have casual sex and there was
no AIDS.

00:06:19.770 --> 00:06:22.810
And you never heard the word "rehab."

00:06:22.810 --> 00:06:26.919
And they were just doing mountains of drugs,
but it was just all in fun.

00:06:26.919 --> 00:06:31.500
I remember there's a brilliant documentary
called "The Decline of Western Civilization-The

00:06:31.500 --> 00:06:35.940
Metal Years," that I literally stole everything
from this movie from.

00:06:35.940 --> 00:06:41.000
And there's an interview with Paul Stanley
from KISS and it starts tight.

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:46.750
And he's clearly under a sheet and he's talking
and just about life and rock and roll.

00:06:46.750 --> 00:06:51.950
And then it pops out, why, he's literally
in bed with four girls, who are also naked.

00:06:51.950 --> 00:06:54.360
And that's how he just did his interview.

00:06:54.360 --> 00:06:55.360
And that was normal.

00:06:55.360 --> 00:06:57.360
So, I thought, "OK.

00:06:57.360 --> 00:06:59.510
I totally get this."

00:06:59.510 --> 00:07:06.650
So, me personally, this music was like really
the wallpaper of my life because--.

00:07:06.650 --> 00:07:12.010
And back when MTV actually played music videos,
every one of these things was on every second.

00:07:12.010 --> 00:07:15.819
So, whether or not you're listening to it
on the radio or had all the--.

00:07:15.819 --> 00:07:16.880
What would they have been now?

00:07:16.880 --> 00:07:19.520
They would've been cassettes, or had the cassette.

00:07:19.520 --> 00:07:21.150
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: On your Walkman.

00:07:21.150 --> 00:07:22.150
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: Yeah.

00:07:22.150 --> 00:07:23.150
On your Walkman.

00:07:23.150 --> 00:07:27.080
There was no way to avoid this music.

00:07:27.080 --> 00:07:30.840
So, it was so entrenched in my consciousness.

00:07:30.840 --> 00:07:35.860
And then, when they asked me to do it and
I went and saw the play, I was barely watching

00:07:35.860 --> 00:07:41.229
the play because I was freaked out about how
out of their minds, the audience was just

00:07:41.229 --> 00:07:42.811
crazy for it.

00:07:42.811 --> 00:07:46.980
They were practically eating their seats.

00:07:46.980 --> 00:07:48.379
And they were all straight.

00:07:48.379 --> 00:07:49.539
In a Broadway musical.

00:07:49.539 --> 00:07:51.169
And they knew all the words.

00:07:51.169 --> 00:07:52.169
[laughter]

00:07:52.169 --> 00:07:54.470
And I thought, "I'll never know an experience
like this again.

00:07:54.470 --> 00:07:57.110
This is an unheard-of moment."

00:07:57.110 --> 00:08:01.840
And so, I thought if I can combine all of
my skills and get that kind of audience, it

00:08:01.840 --> 00:08:03.780
would be an amazing experience.

00:08:03.780 --> 00:08:07.949
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: And was it one of the biggest
challenges of actually working on this movie?

00:08:07.949 --> 00:08:09.629
Just getting the songs out of your head?

00:08:09.629 --> 00:08:11.270
I mean, if you hear the same songs--.

00:08:11.270 --> 00:08:12.270
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: Oh, yeah.

00:08:12.270 --> 00:08:13.270
God.

00:08:13.270 --> 00:08:14.270
It's, well now--.

00:08:14.270 --> 00:08:15.270
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: every single one up there,
you just--.

00:08:15.270 --> 00:08:16.270
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: Well, they're on the radio
all the time.

00:08:16.270 --> 00:08:19.760
I mean, "We're Not Gonna Take It" is now like
a hotel commercial--the theme song.

00:08:19.760 --> 00:08:25.190
So, and they use it as a bit about coffee,
about "we're not gonna take bad coffee anymore."

00:08:25.190 --> 00:08:26.190
[laughter]

00:08:26.190 --> 00:08:29.580
I'm sure that's what the song was originally
intended to be about.

00:08:29.580 --> 00:08:30.580
[laughter]

00:08:30.580 --> 00:08:32.750
They went back to the roots.

00:08:32.750 --> 00:08:39.060
But the biggest challenge for me with this,
because it is jukebox musical and this is

00:08:39.060 --> 00:08:42.930
the nature of jukebox musicals, is that the
songs are not written for a character.

00:08:42.930 --> 00:08:49.000
So, you have to mold everything around those
words coming out of people's mouths.

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:54.100
I mean, in this movie, there's the production.

00:08:54.100 --> 00:08:58.570
There's the numbers that are presentational
on stage, and there's dialogue and there's

00:08:58.570 --> 00:09:00.770
monologues--stuff going on in people's heads.

00:09:00.770 --> 00:09:05.790
So, it was just a matter of putting the right
words and keeping everybody who they are and

00:09:05.790 --> 00:09:07.130
real.

00:09:07.130 --> 00:09:08.760
As real as you can be in this world.

00:09:08.760 --> 00:09:13.010
But by the way, this is a real world for me
because I actually do sing and dance regularly

00:09:13.010 --> 00:09:16.410
in my life and am a true embarrassment to
the gym.

00:09:16.410 --> 00:09:17.410
[laughter]

00:09:17.410 --> 00:09:19.290
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: So, where were you in 1987?

00:09:19.290 --> 00:09:24.610
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: 1987, I was in New York.

00:09:24.610 --> 00:09:26.280
And I was more of like a club kid.

00:09:26.280 --> 00:09:29.570
Back then, I was more New Wave-y.

00:09:29.570 --> 00:09:35.370
But I got back to LA--I'm from LA--and I got
back to LA.

00:09:35.370 --> 00:09:36.630
Yeah.

00:09:36.630 --> 00:09:44.260
I had left school and I was a waiter and had
just started doing, I started working in theater--musical

00:09:44.260 --> 00:09:45.260
theater.

00:09:45.260 --> 00:09:47.820
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: 'Cause you went to Julliard
at 18 and--.

00:09:47.820 --> 00:09:49.260
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: Yeah.

00:09:49.260 --> 00:09:50.260
Yeah.

00:09:50.260 --> 00:09:51.339
And I dropped out soon after.

00:09:51.339 --> 00:09:53.874
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: But you actually got in
without actually having had a dance class.

00:09:53.874 --> 00:09:54.874
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: Having ever had a dance class.

00:09:54.874 --> 00:09:55.874
I know.

00:09:55.874 --> 00:09:56.874
I was a weird one.

00:09:56.874 --> 00:09:57.874
I was Flashdance.

00:09:57.874 --> 00:10:00.470
It was literally, it was me in leg warmers,
dancing.

00:10:00.470 --> 00:10:01.470
[laughter]

00:10:01.470 --> 00:10:04.970
And I had never taken a dance class and they
let me in.

00:10:04.970 --> 00:10:09.940
And I got into every school that I auditioned
for without ever having had a dance class,

00:10:09.940 --> 00:10:11.490
which all it means is I'm a good imitator.

00:10:11.490 --> 00:10:12.529
Do you know what I mean?

00:10:12.529 --> 00:10:15.610
It's like I knew where to put my leg at the
right moment, whatever.

00:10:15.610 --> 00:10:20.120
But that was really crazy, that audition,
because they have a very strict ballet bar.

00:10:20.120 --> 00:10:21.870
And I didn't know what any of the words were.

00:10:21.870 --> 00:10:24.910
I kind of knew what a plie was, but past that,
I had never heard it.

00:10:24.910 --> 00:10:27.142
So, I'm just looking at everybody, trying
to just get past the audition.

00:10:27.142 --> 00:10:28.142
It was crazy.

00:10:28.142 --> 00:10:31.690
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: And New York didn't really
hold you in sway?

00:10:31.690 --> 00:10:33.420
And you, back home for?

00:10:33.420 --> 00:10:39.890
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: Well, honestly, I had just
done some summer stock and I had my first

00:10:39.890 --> 00:10:40.930
relationship.

00:10:40.930 --> 00:10:43.380
And it ended really weirdly.

00:10:43.380 --> 00:10:47.899
He flipped out and so, I moved and my parents
said, "Just please come back home."

00:10:47.899 --> 00:10:50.660
And I moved back to LA.

00:10:50.660 --> 00:10:53.420
This was my dream to become a video music
producer.

00:10:53.420 --> 00:10:56.980
And then, I ended up working at a restaurant.

00:10:56.980 --> 00:11:04.570
And then, got in, I auditioned for another
Janet Jackson "Escapade" video, so I'm in

00:11:04.570 --> 00:11:05.570
