into my first choreography gig and never looked

00:11:25.630 --> 00:11:26.630
back.

00:11:26.630 --> 00:11:28.800
I was only 24 when I started choreographing.

00:11:28.800 --> 00:11:29.800
So--.

00:11:29.800 --> 00:11:34.430
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: And having grown up in Hollywood,
you probably had folks you knew, or friends

00:11:34.430 --> 00:11:37.320
of parents, who were in the movie business
in some way, shape, or form.

00:11:37.320 --> 00:11:39.660
You never really though about movies as such,
or--?

00:11:39.660 --> 00:11:42.149
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: Well, I never wanted to be
a director.

00:11:42.149 --> 00:11:44.120
God, that never even occurred to me.

00:11:44.120 --> 00:11:50.700
But what the choreography thing what was really
cool was I had all these friends who are part

00:11:50.700 --> 00:11:56.519
of a young Hollywood organization called Young
Artists United.

00:11:56.519 --> 00:12:03.589
And my friend Patrick, who actually started
Rock the Vote, was the head of this thing.

00:12:03.589 --> 00:12:07.181
And it was all people like Judd Nelson and
Sarah Jessica Parker and Robert Downey, who

00:12:07.181 --> 00:12:10.459
I lived with when they were together.

00:12:10.459 --> 00:12:14.670
They were my roommates.

00:12:14.670 --> 00:12:15.730
[chuckles]

00:12:15.730 --> 00:12:19.170
They would go around to schools and preach
like not doing drugs and drinking.

00:12:19.170 --> 00:12:20.170
[laughter]

00:12:20.170 --> 00:12:22.310
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: They did their research.

00:12:22.310 --> 00:12:23.660
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: Yeah.

00:12:23.660 --> 00:12:29.949
And so, what started happening with all these
friends of mine is they started to just become

00:12:29.949 --> 00:12:30.949
movie stars.

00:12:30.949 --> 00:12:35.670
And they started to ask for me on their movies.

00:12:35.670 --> 00:12:41.540
I was their friend who was the choreographer
and so, that was them flexing their new muscles.

00:12:41.540 --> 00:12:44.230
And so, that's how I started in the movie
thing.

00:12:44.230 --> 00:12:47.620
But before then, it was a lot of music videos--tons
and tons and tons of music videos.

00:12:47.620 --> 00:12:49.480
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: But your sister is a producer
as well.

00:12:49.480 --> 00:12:53.279
Did you guys ever say, "Hey, when we grow
up, we're gonna dive in?"

00:12:53.279 --> 00:12:54.279
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: No.

00:12:54.279 --> 00:12:55.279
We never said that.

00:12:55.279 --> 00:12:56.279
No.

00:12:56.279 --> 00:12:57.279
We were more like saying, "I hate you."

00:12:57.279 --> 00:12:58.279
"No, I hate you."

00:12:58.279 --> 00:12:59.279
"I hate you."

00:12:59.279 --> 00:13:02.899
We were, she is five years younger than me.

00:13:02.899 --> 00:13:07.029
She was working for a company and she produced
the movie "She's All That."

00:13:07.029 --> 00:13:10.470
And she asked me to choreograph.

00:13:10.470 --> 00:13:14.449
And there's like a big prom scene and there's
some other weird stuff in there that I had

00:13:14.449 --> 00:13:15.790
worked on.

00:13:15.790 --> 00:13:19.290
And she thought I was good and she thought
I should be a director.

00:13:19.290 --> 00:13:21.240
And I said, "But I don't know what you're
talking about."

00:13:21.240 --> 00:13:27.029
And I was actually, at that point, I had honestly
choreographed like, 70 movies in like, ten

00:13:27.029 --> 00:13:31.360
or eleven years, and a million TV shows and
commercials.

00:13:31.360 --> 00:13:37.360
And I was getting a fatigue from directors
that I found to be challenging that they couldn't

00:13:37.360 --> 00:13:38.680
make decisions.

00:13:38.680 --> 00:13:42.720
And so, I pulled it together and I spent my
own money and made a short film.

00:13:42.720 --> 00:13:46.150
And the producer of that short film, without
asking me, submitted it to Sundance and it

00:13:46.150 --> 00:13:47.150
got in.

00:13:47.150 --> 00:13:48.530
And the rest is history.

00:13:48.530 --> 00:13:49.530
[laughter]

00:13:49.530 --> 00:13:53.110
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: So, it sounds like through
osmosis, just being exposed and on sets--

00:13:53.110 --> 00:13:54.110
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: Oh, yeah.

00:13:54.110 --> 00:13:56.140
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: all that kind of nuance
and the different roles within--.

00:13:56.140 --> 00:13:57.490
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: I did not go to school for
that.

00:13:57.490 --> 00:13:59.920
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: the industry, you just got
exposed to it and took it on.

00:13:59.920 --> 00:14:00.920
So, script writing.

00:14:00.920 --> 00:14:04.290
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: Well, the best part is that
my parents--my mom's a shrink and my dad was

00:14:04.290 --> 00:14:10.130
a lawyer--so my whole approach to actors is
assess and negotiate.

00:14:10.130 --> 00:14:11.680
[laughter]

00:14:11.680 --> 00:14:13.720
And it's on a case-by-case basis.

00:14:13.720 --> 00:14:14.720
[laughter]

00:14:14.720 --> 00:14:15.720
It's how it's worked for me.

00:14:15.720 --> 00:14:20.730
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: And as far as assess and
negotiate with regards to just every component

00:14:20.730 --> 00:14:23.899
of the movie industry because it's always,
I think, from the outside, you pick up on

00:14:23.899 --> 00:14:28.440
different words as far as something being
green-lit and multiple producers versus an

00:14:28.440 --> 00:14:30.300
executive producer and all these different
roles.

00:14:30.300 --> 00:14:34.279
And it seems just like, well, it's obviously
herding cats and it's extremely complex and

00:14:34.279 --> 00:14:38.420
difficult, but how did you get comfortable
in each of those roles?

00:14:38.420 --> 00:14:41.470
So, for example, just getting to how scripts
work?

00:14:41.470 --> 00:14:42.850
How script formats worked?

00:14:42.850 --> 00:14:47.149
Act one, two, three, when certain types of
events should happen?

00:14:47.149 --> 00:14:51.130
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: Well, I'd been through so
many and I've seen so many people go up and

00:14:51.130 --> 00:14:53.170
I've seen so many people come down.

00:14:53.170 --> 00:14:56.710
And being a crew member, as a choreographer,
I'm just a crew member.

00:14:56.710 --> 00:14:58.440
And knowing--.

00:14:58.440 --> 00:14:59.670
And you really get to know--.

00:14:59.670 --> 00:15:03.360
And by the way, as a choreographer, I am also
directing the actors in the scenes.

00:15:03.360 --> 00:15:07.310
I was hired to do a lot of scenes with the
leads in the thing 'cause scripts say "and

00:15:07.310 --> 00:15:08.310
then they dance."

00:15:08.310 --> 00:15:10.519
And so, that's where I come in.

00:15:10.519 --> 00:15:14.009
So, I had already worked a lot with actors.

00:15:14.009 --> 00:15:16.420
I knew a lot of actors growing up.

00:15:16.420 --> 00:15:19.040
My dad represented a bunch.

00:15:19.040 --> 00:15:23.759
And I saw, I never learned anything from a
good director.

00:15:23.759 --> 00:15:25.980
I literally never learned anything from a
good director.

00:15:25.980 --> 00:15:31.190
I learned a lot from the bad ones because
I was like, "God, I never wanna be that person.

00:15:31.190 --> 00:15:33.520
I never wanna treat people that way."

00:15:33.520 --> 00:15:36.880
There's a long list of "I never want."

00:15:36.880 --> 00:15:39.440
And so, but the good ones are just magic.

00:15:39.440 --> 00:15:41.130
Like, you don't understand what's happening.

00:15:41.130 --> 00:15:43.440
They're just creating something great.

00:15:43.440 --> 00:15:53.069
And when I started directing, I just, you
just go with your gut.

00:15:53.069 --> 00:15:56.160
It's all weird opportunities.

00:15:56.160 --> 00:16:01.170
And I never take it for granted that this
is my job and this is an opportunity and that

00:16:01.170 --> 00:16:05.160
this is a privilege and that these people
are entrusting me with a bunch of money.

00:16:05.160 --> 00:16:07.850
And the actors are trusting me with their
careers.

00:16:07.850 --> 00:16:13.019
And I take it seriously in that I'm not better
than any of the project, the this, the actor,

00:16:13.019 --> 00:16:14.019
the any of it.

00:16:14.019 --> 00:16:19.730
So really, again in the assess and negotiate
thing, what I learned very early on is choosing

00:16:19.730 --> 00:16:24.029
which swords you're gonna fall on because
there are so many battles that you wage.

00:16:24.029 --> 00:16:29.420
And some of them feel very personal and they're
not, but they feel like it.

00:16:29.420 --> 00:16:34.459
And certainly the more I've gone on, the more
I get frustrated because I feel like I've

00:16:34.459 --> 00:16:39.170
proven myself literally over and over and
over and over again in so many different areas.

00:16:39.170 --> 00:16:44.889
And but it is everybody's job to treat you
without trust.

00:16:44.889 --> 00:16:47.889
It feels like they're all really behind you
until that moment, you know?

00:16:47.889 --> 00:16:48.970
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Yeah.

00:16:48.970 --> 00:16:51.860
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: Then, it's just like a disaster.

00:16:51.860 --> 00:16:56.380
And then, I have a tough side.

00:16:56.380 --> 00:16:57.519
And I get--.

00:16:57.519 --> 00:16:59.560
My eyes narrow and I can--.

00:16:59.560 --> 00:17:03.839
Once again, that's where the shrink and lawyer
part comes in, which is really good is because

00:17:03.839 --> 00:17:05.839
I go for everybody's Achilles heel.

00:17:05.839 --> 00:17:08.980
I go right for what's gonna hurt them the
most, you know?

00:17:08.980 --> 00:17:09.980
[laughter]

00:17:09.980 --> 00:17:13.841
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Well, as you shifted into
different roles, oftentimes you actually were

00:17:13.841 --> 00:17:14.841
doing two roles.

00:17:14.841 --> 00:17:15.841
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: Yeah.

00:17:15.841 --> 00:17:16.841
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: So, you'd choreograph and
you would direct.

00:17:16.841 --> 00:17:18.920
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: Choreographing, directing,
producing--it's all part of it.

00:17:18.920 --> 00:17:21.290
I mean, and you can't really effectively--.

00:17:21.290 --> 00:17:22.850
I mean, let's put it this way.

00:17:22.850 --> 00:17:27.500
"Hairspray" was much easier because I had
choreographed it for me because I was choreographing

00:17:27.500 --> 00:17:28.580
for camera.

00:17:28.580 --> 00:17:33.220
So, when "Rock of Ages," I had, there was
only five weeks of prep and it was a much

00:17:33.220 --> 00:17:35.310
bigger movie--same budget as "Hairspray."

00:17:35.310 --> 00:17:38.350
It was literally, we were like, "You have
to back into a number."

00:17:38.350 --> 00:17:39.970
And so, I said OK.

00:17:39.970 --> 00:17:42.410
And we did it.

00:17:42.410 --> 00:17:47.010
But I hired a very good colleague, who I think
is one of the greatest choreographers on Earth

00:17:47.010 --> 00:17:48.010
right now.

00:17:48.010 --> 00:17:50.660
It's this woman, Mia Michaels, and she choreographed
it.

00:17:50.660 --> 00:17:55.300
And we have some Mia fans.

00:17:55.300 --> 00:17:56.300
[laughter]

00:17:56.300 --> 00:18:02.930
And then, she's more of like, an artists-type
and wasn't used to working on strict production

00:18:02.930 --> 00:18:05.920
schedules and "I need this now," and yadda
yadda yadda.

00:18:05.920 --> 00:18:11.760
On top of which, I was asking her to do stuff
that was so like she had never done before,

00:18:11.760 --> 00:18:13.350
which were sex.

00:18:13.350 --> 00:18:17.960
She does not sexualize anything and I have
all these strippers in the movie, boy band

00:18:17.960 --> 00:18:19.330
choreography, which she was like--.

00:18:19.330 --> 00:18:22.710
I was like, "No, it actually needs to be the
Roger Rabbit.

00:18:22.710 --> 00:18:24.940
It needs to actually be--."

00:18:24.940 --> 00:18:26.690
Like I want them to go like this.

00:18:26.690 --> 00:18:27.690
[laughter]

00:18:27.690 --> 00:18:33.730
She was like, "I don't know who I am anymore."

00:18:33.730 --> 00:18:37.760
And she'd cry and it was amazing.

00:18:37.760 --> 00:18:39.470
[laughter]

00:18:39.470 --> 00:18:42.620
And so that was that.

00:18:42.620 --> 00:18:47.520
But that was hard because I would come in
to watch a rehearsal and I wouldn't be familiar

00:18:47.520 --> 00:18:49.260
with all the stuff right away.

00:18:49.260 --> 00:18:50.260
But, you know?

00:18:50.260 --> 00:18:52.030
That's what I do, so I was very quick to figure
it out.

00:18:52.030 --> 00:18:56.020
There were times when we would be shooting
and she hadn't finished the number.

00:18:56.020 --> 00:18:58.750
And so, she was making it up as we were going
along.

00:18:58.750 --> 00:19:02.080
And it was four o'clock in the morning and
I'm like, "Can you show me what's next?"

00:19:02.080 --> 00:19:03.290
And she's like, "I'm not sure what's next."

00:19:03.290 --> 00:19:06.080
And I was like, "Can we figure it out?"

00:19:06.080 --> 00:19:07.080
[laughter]

00:19:07.080 --> 00:19:10.610
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: But oftentimes, those can
be the best moments for inspiration, right,

00:19:10.610 --> 00:19:12.630
when you've just gone through the other side.

00:19:12.630 --> 00:19:13.980
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: I mean, I, listen.

00:19:13.980 --> 00:19:15.540
I'm an adrenaline junkie.

00:19:15.540 --> 00:19:17.850
So, I live for that stuff.

00:19:17.850 --> 00:19:23.940
And actually, it's in the most dire, most
horrible moments that I go the most calm,

00:19:23.940 --> 00:19:24.940
you know?

00:19:24.940 --> 00:19:29.840
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Well, back to being able
to preserve your energy so you can put your,

00:19:29.840 --> 00:19:31.590
the most in the right spots--?

00:19:31.590 --> 00:19:32.590
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: Yeah.

00:19:32.590 --> 00:19:35.090
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: When you start to take on
producing, directing, and choreography, how

00:19:35.090 --> 00:19:39.801
much more time would that add to a movie being,
when you're planning because you're on the

00:19:39.801 --> 00:19:40.860
set, you just--?

00:19:40.860 --> 00:19:41.860
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: You know what?

00:19:41.860 --> 00:19:43.780
I'm not really good at living in the world.

00:19:43.780 --> 00:19:45.440
I'm really good at living on set.

00:19:45.440 --> 00:19:47.230
And so, I'm just happy there.

00:19:47.230 --> 00:19:48.510
And so, it's all good.

00:19:48.510 --> 00:19:49.721
Do you know what I mean?

00:19:49.721 --> 00:19:53.100
I would love to say, "Oh, it's so grueling."

00:19:53.100 --> 00:19:54.100
It's not.

00:19:54.100 --> 00:19:55.440
I love it so much.

00:19:55.440 --> 00:19:56.440
[laughter]

00:19:56.440 --> 00:19:57.960
It's so much a better place for me.

00:19:57.960 --> 00:20:05.750
And me, running amok in the world, bad, bad,
bad, bad, bad.

00:20:05.750 --> 00:20:11.770
So, I just started writing my first screenplay,
which I was very excited about, that I actually

00:20:11.770 --> 00:20:17.160
have the nerve to like, think that I could
look at a blank page and have something to

00:20:17.160 --> 00:20:18.160
say.

00:20:18.160 --> 00:20:23.080
I imagine it's gonna be horrible, but I'm
excited.

00:20:23.080 --> 00:20:25.320
And like, I'm not talking about--

00:20:25.320 --> 00:20:26.320
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: You'd be old?

00:20:26.320 --> 00:20:27.320
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: writing.

00:20:27.320 --> 00:20:31.090
I'm writing a children's book series, potentially.

00:20:31.090 --> 00:20:32.970
So, I've started doing that.

00:20:32.970 --> 00:20:34.430
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: In addition to the screen
plays and then you're also--.

00:20:34.430 --> 00:20:35.430
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: Yeah.

00:20:35.430 --> 00:20:37.460
Well, that for some reason is much easier
for me.

00:20:37.460 --> 00:20:38.460
I don't know why.

00:20:38.460 --> 00:20:39.700
I don't know why.

00:20:39.700 --> 00:20:41.081
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Children's series.

00:20:41.081 --> 00:20:42.081
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: Do you know why?

00:20:42.081 --> 00:20:43.081
[laughter]

00:20:43.081 --> 00:20:47.820
I come, like, a lot of my background is children's
theater, so I'm very versed in that.

00:20:47.820 --> 00:20:50.570
So, and it's weird 'cause I'm like a dirty
old man.

00:20:50.570 --> 00:20:51.570
[laughter]

00:20:51.570 --> 00:20:52.570
So, it's weird.

00:20:52.570 --> 00:20:53.570
I mean, I'm not, but I-- [laughs]

00:20:53.570 --> 00:20:54.570
[laughter]

00:20:54.570 --> 00:20:55.570
Not really, but I'm like a person who's lived
in the world.

00:20:55.570 --> 00:20:56.570
Yeah.

00:20:56.570 --> 00:20:57.570
Yeah.

00:20:57.570 --> 00:20:58.570
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: You just happen to choreograph
strippers.

00:20:58.570 --> 00:21:03.810
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: I mean, but the strippers
in my movie are like Cirque du Soleil performers.

00:21:03.810 --> 00:21:05.590
They're like, they're non-strippers.

00:21:05.590 --> 00:21:07.410
They're professional pole specialists.

00:21:07.410 --> 00:21:08.410
[laughter]

00:21:08.410 --> 00:21:13.310
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Now, trying to actually
control that environment, because to your

00:21:13.310 --> 00:21:18.530
point, that time was so drugs, sex, and rock
and roll, and obviously, this is a look into

00:21:18.530 --> 00:21:20.750
that at a window.

00:21:20.750 --> 00:21:24.470
Did some of that seep into the environment
on the set and you had to keep that control?

00:21:24.470 --> 00:21:25.470
Or, were you enthusiastically--everyone was
super?

00:21:25.470 --> 00:21:26.470
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: Oh, God.

00:21:26.470 --> 00:21:27.470
No, no, no, no.

00:21:27.470 --> 00:21:28.470
Everybody's super.

00:21:28.470 --> 00:21:30.870
I mean, don't get me wrong.

00:21:30.870 --> 00:21:40.330
When you're around Tom, there's just no room
for any of that--Tom Cruise.

00:21:40.330 --> 00:21:41.330
Tom.

00:21:41.330 --> 00:21:42.330
[laughter]

00:21:42.330 --> 00:21:43.330
So, yep.

00:21:43.330 --> 00:21:44.330
Tom.

00:21:44.330 --> 00:21:50.260
He sets a bar of professionalism that is so
beyond anything you can possibly imagine.

00:21:50.260 --> 00:21:53.300
His enthusiasm, his energy.

00:21:53.300 --> 00:21:55.830
He's there two hours before the crew.

00:21:55.830 --> 00:22:02.560
It's embarrassing 'cause you're constantly
trying to live up to that, that standard of

00:22:02.560 --> 00:22:05.390
professionalism and commitment.

00:22:05.390 --> 00:22:07.670
And that's my whole thing.

00:22:07.670 --> 00:22:08.670
It's like, "Look.

00:22:08.670 --> 00:22:13.350
My life is too short and living on sets, they
have to be happy sets or I'll kill people."

00:22:13.350 --> 00:22:15.420
Like, you're happy or you're fired.

00:22:15.420 --> 00:22:23.590
It's basically my philosophy, so I insist
that it be a fertile, happy environ--.

00:22:23.590 --> 00:22:27.530
I mean, even when I was making "A Walk to
Remember," which is and then she died of cancer

00:22:27.530 --> 00:22:30.250
movie, I was a happy set.

00:22:30.250 --> 00:22:31.250
[laughter]

00:22:31.250 --> 00:22:34.170
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Well, I think that must
help bringing an ensemble cast.

00:22:34.170 --> 00:22:36.090
I mean, that's quite a cast.

00:22:36.090 --> 00:22:37.460
It's Paul Giamatti.

00:22:37.460 --> 00:22:39.480
It's Mary J. Blige.

00:22:39.480 --> 00:22:40.840
It's Tom.

00:22:40.840 --> 00:22:41.840
It's Alec Baldwin.

00:22:41.840 --> 00:22:42.840
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: Everybody.

00:22:42.840 --> 00:22:43.840
Yeah, yeah.

00:22:43.840 --> 00:22:45.910
It's, and everybody in a different level of
something and definitely big personalities.

00:22:45.910 --> 00:22:50.560
And but, in a musical, because it's none of
their forte--except for Catherine--that Catherine

00:22:50.560 --> 00:22:52.260
Zeta-Jones.

00:22:52.260 --> 00:22:53.960
Catherine.

00:22:53.960 --> 00:22:55.660
[laughter]

00:22:55.660 --> 00:23:02.360
Other than Catherine Zeta-Jones, because they're
out of their comfort zone, everybody was really

00:23:02.360 --> 00:23:04.650
into it and really, incredibly--.

00:23:04.650 --> 00:23:06.420
You know, it's a hard thing.

00:23:06.420 --> 00:23:07.420
You have to really rehearse.

00:23:07.420 --> 00:23:13.070
I mean, Tom Cruise literally willed a totally
different person onto himself--the way he

00:23:13.070 --> 00:23:14.070
walks, his singing.

00:23:14.070 --> 00:23:19.120
He was singing four, five hours a day for
that many months.

00:23:19.120 --> 00:23:22.700
And I got scared he was gonna blow out his
voice.

00:23:22.700 --> 00:23:23.700
But it's insane.

00:23:23.700 --> 00:23:28.340
I mean, it's amazing the product that comes
out of that.

00:23:28.340 --> 00:23:34.400
For this, this movie is just like a party,
but the work that went into it was incredible.

