You know what I mean?

00:34:58.570 --> 00:34:59.570
[laughter]

00:34:59.570 --> 00:35:01.760
It's like, and get Zac Efron.

00:35:01.760 --> 00:35:05.130
So, that one was kind of easy.

00:35:05.130 --> 00:35:06.820
But I, you know what?

00:35:06.820 --> 00:35:14.100
My godson, who's two and a half, if I can
get him away from the "Backyardigans," he

00:35:14.100 --> 00:35:15.100
loves musicals.

00:35:15.100 --> 00:35:16.450
He loves all the old MGM musicals.

00:35:16.450 --> 00:35:19.460
He loves, and those are just, those last forever.

00:35:19.460 --> 00:35:20.950
So, the new ones.

00:35:20.950 --> 00:35:24.540
I mean, this one was sexy on purpose.

00:35:24.540 --> 00:35:27.160
But it's inherent to the world.

00:35:27.160 --> 00:35:29.520
But more are gettin' made.

00:35:29.520 --> 00:35:31.500
More are going to get made.

00:35:31.500 --> 00:35:36.770
&gt;&gt;Female #1: I have three somewhat related
questions about Tom.

00:35:36.770 --> 00:35:37.770
[laughter]

00:35:37.770 --> 00:35:39.010
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: I'm shocked.

00:35:39.010 --> 00:35:40.010
[laughter]

00:35:40.010 --> 00:35:43.650
&gt;&gt;Female #1: So, why Tom Cruise for the role
of Stacee Jaxx?

00:35:43.650 --> 00:35:48.960
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: Because he was, he and Suri,
who basically rules that household, was a

00:35:48.960 --> 00:35:50.850
huge "Hairspray" fan.

00:35:50.850 --> 00:35:56.650
And they watched it probably 300 times, apparently.

00:35:56.650 --> 00:35:59.270
And I met him at a party.

00:35:59.270 --> 00:36:04.170
Actually, at a one year old's birthday party,
literally sitting in one of those little baby

00:36:04.170 --> 00:36:05.170
chairs.

00:36:05.170 --> 00:36:06.170
[laughter]

00:36:06.170 --> 00:36:08.020
And he pulled up one next to me and started
talking to me.

00:36:08.020 --> 00:36:09.070
And he was like, "Hey, I'm Tom Cruise."

00:36:09.070 --> 00:36:11.640
And I was like, "I know who you are."

00:36:11.640 --> 00:36:12.640
[laughter]

00:36:12.640 --> 00:36:16.590
"Why am I in a baby chair meeting Tom Cruise?"

00:36:16.590 --> 00:36:19.740
And I actually stood up and it stuck to my
ass.

00:36:19.740 --> 00:36:20.790
[laughter]

00:36:20.790 --> 00:36:21.810
And this is not a joke.

00:36:21.810 --> 00:36:23.910
That is a very true story.

00:36:23.910 --> 00:36:24.910
It made him laugh.

00:36:24.910 --> 00:36:29.170
He made some reference to wanting to do a
musical and I was like, "That's great and

00:36:29.170 --> 00:36:30.800
that will never happen."

00:36:30.800 --> 00:36:35.110
And then, this came along and I thought, "God,
if I could get the biggest movie star in the

00:36:35.110 --> 00:36:39.330
world to play the biggest rock star in the
world, that would be an event."

00:36:39.330 --> 00:36:44.850
And I certainly don't want to put out a musical,
put my name on something that's a musical,

00:36:44.850 --> 00:36:48.870
that's my home, what I love the most, and
then not have people want to see it.

00:36:48.870 --> 00:36:49.870
Do you know what I mean?

00:36:49.870 --> 00:36:54.380
So, I knew, it seems stunty, but it's still--.

00:36:54.380 --> 00:36:57.330
By the way, how many people here saw it?

00:36:57.330 --> 00:36:59.270
Dude pulled it off, right?

00:36:59.270 --> 00:37:05.110
I mean, like that was a lot of work that went
into that.

00:37:05.110 --> 00:37:06.280
And it was a gamble that payed off.

00:37:06.280 --> 00:37:09.910
&gt;&gt;Female #1: So, kind of a follow-up, how
difficult was it for him to get into that

00:37:09.910 --> 00:37:11.050
role and what did he have to do?

00:37:11.050 --> 00:37:16.740
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: We poured over, I sent him
every book known to mankind about those guys

00:37:16.740 --> 00:37:17.740
in this period.

00:37:17.740 --> 00:37:24.330
And I talked to him endlessly about channeling
his intensity into being intensely lost.

00:37:24.330 --> 00:37:30.050
I wanted him just to like, not be a creature
of the world nobody says no to.

00:37:30.050 --> 00:37:36.870
And who, certainly Tom is not a stranger to
the notion of being a star.

00:37:36.870 --> 00:37:41.450
So, that was an easy in for him, but he, the
guy doesn't drink.

00:37:41.450 --> 00:37:44.130
To my knowledge, he never touched a drug.

00:37:44.130 --> 00:37:47.500
So, this is all very foreign.

00:37:47.500 --> 00:37:49.550
But he loved, it just made him laugh.

00:37:49.550 --> 00:37:54.130
The whole thing, he just thought it was so
weird that I was asking him to do a musical.

00:37:54.130 --> 00:37:55.371
And he just loved the opportunity.

00:37:55.371 --> 00:38:01.810
And especially being a father and Suri being
this incredibly creative, beautiful child,

00:38:01.810 --> 00:38:04.270
he loved having music in the house a lot.

00:38:04.270 --> 00:38:07.930
So, it really, it did a lot in their family
life.

00:38:07.930 --> 00:38:14.320
Poor Katie has to listen to the guy sing now
every minute of the day, but the dude has

00:38:14.320 --> 00:38:16.690
the loudest voice on the planet.

00:38:16.690 --> 00:38:17.690
[laughter]

00:38:17.690 --> 00:38:18.690
Decibel breaking.

00:38:18.690 --> 00:38:23.160
&gt;&gt;Female #1: You touched on just a little
bit, but just in general, what's it like to

00:38:23.160 --> 00:38:24.160
work with him?

00:38:24.160 --> 00:38:26.580
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: He was the greatest experience
of my life.

00:38:26.580 --> 00:38:33.850
It was absolutely life-changing just in terms
of having to look at myself and just say,

00:38:33.850 --> 00:38:38.160
"How present am I?"

00:38:38.160 --> 00:38:43.330
And just really seeing, there's zero ego.

00:38:43.330 --> 00:38:45.980
There is just the work.

00:38:45.980 --> 00:38:47.880
And that is so inspiring.

00:38:47.880 --> 00:38:48.890
That is so inspiring.

00:38:48.890 --> 00:38:53.640
There's been a few actors that I've worked
with that have really taught me a lot.

00:38:53.640 --> 00:38:56.170
Michelle Pfeiffer was one of them.

00:38:56.170 --> 00:38:57.750
Michelle.

00:38:57.750 --> 00:38:59.330
[laughter]

00:38:59.330 --> 00:39:00.330
On and on.

00:39:00.330 --> 00:39:04.690
I've had the great pleasure of working with
people who really take what they do seriously.

00:39:04.690 --> 00:39:08.240
And I take what I do seriously because it's
all I do.

00:39:08.240 --> 00:39:10.150
I mean, this is amazing.

00:39:10.150 --> 00:39:13.520
I can't believe like I'm out of my editing
room or something like that.

00:39:13.520 --> 00:39:15.380
It's like, "Oh, wow.

00:39:15.380 --> 00:39:16.380
There's people."

00:39:16.380 --> 00:39:17.570
So, it's great.

00:39:17.570 --> 00:39:18.910
It was amazing.

00:39:18.910 --> 00:39:20.750
He is as--.

00:39:20.750 --> 00:39:22.830
You know what's really funny about him?

00:39:22.830 --> 00:39:27.380
When I look back now and think about the Oprah
thing and any of that stuff, that's real.

00:39:27.380 --> 00:39:28.890
Like, he gets that excited.

00:39:28.890 --> 00:39:31.990
He's like a kid.

00:39:31.990 --> 00:39:36.510
He's guileless and just, he just loves stuff.

00:39:36.510 --> 00:39:37.590
And that's real.

00:39:37.590 --> 00:39:42.950
And so, sometimes, I was like, "You have to
stop liking this movie so much.

00:39:42.950 --> 00:39:45.420
Please, you're killing me, dude."

00:39:45.420 --> 00:39:46.420
[laughter]

00:39:46.420 --> 00:39:48.050
But he just never wanted it to end.

00:39:48.050 --> 00:39:51.050
&gt;&gt;Male #2: Hi.

00:39:51.050 --> 00:39:53.430
First, my wife and I saw the movie last night.

00:39:53.430 --> 00:39:54.430
We loved it.

00:39:54.430 --> 00:39:55.430
It was fantastic.

00:39:55.430 --> 00:39:56.430
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: Mm-hmm.

00:39:56.430 --> 00:39:59.210
&gt;&gt;Male #2: And this question may be a little
bit too close to your work for most people,

00:39:59.210 --> 00:40:01.230
but I'm a product manager in the Ads group.

00:40:01.230 --> 00:40:06.840
I work on tracking how online advertising
affects people's activities in the real world.

00:40:06.840 --> 00:40:10.520
I was wondering if you could tell us anything
you're doing or that you know people in Hollywood

00:40:10.520 --> 00:40:14.550
are doing with regards to integrating the
internet into movies and things in general?

00:40:14.550 --> 00:40:15.550
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: Oh, my God.

00:40:15.550 --> 00:40:20.680
It's a huge part of our discussions during
the marketing of a movie.

00:40:20.680 --> 00:40:32.850
They're now partially predicting openings
by Twitter activity, trending, certainly an

00:40:32.850 --> 00:40:39.570
active Facebook page, anything that's interactive
with a greater audience.

00:40:39.570 --> 00:40:40.890
It's a big part of our discussions.

00:40:40.890 --> 00:40:45.060
&gt;&gt;Male #2: Do you do anything with things
that are more than just tracking ads, but

00:40:45.060 --> 00:40:46.440
also live interaction?

00:40:46.440 --> 00:40:48.520
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: Aren't I doing it right now?

00:40:48.520 --> 00:40:49.520
[laughter]

00:40:49.520 --> 00:40:52.100
&gt;&gt;Male #2: Well, I'll give you a specific
example.

00:40:52.100 --> 00:40:54.180
In New York, there's a group called Punchdrunk.

00:40:54.180 --> 00:40:55.180
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: Uh-huh.

00:40:55.180 --> 00:40:58.190
&gt;&gt;Male #2: And they do this live, interactive
theater example experience.

00:40:58.190 --> 00:41:05.970
And they're working on some things where you
integrate the live experience with the internet

00:41:05.970 --> 00:41:10.660
experience, so that there's something happening
simultaneously.

00:41:10.660 --> 00:41:13.770
And there are other people who have done things
with voting systems and things like that.

00:41:13.770 --> 00:41:18.090
Is there anything experimental you know of
or anything that--?

00:41:18.090 --> 00:41:22.040
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: I don't know about it, but
I'm sure there is.

00:41:22.040 --> 00:41:32.130
A guy who I, a young director who I gave his
first job, he did the second and third "Step

00:41:32.130 --> 00:41:33.590
Up" movies--Jon Chu.

00:41:33.590 --> 00:41:35.380
And he just did "GI Joe."

00:41:35.380 --> 00:41:38.430
YouTube just gave him a whole channel.

00:41:38.430 --> 00:41:41.890
And that's all about dance stuff, material.

00:41:41.890 --> 00:41:44.950
And I know he's doing lots of different kinds
of work like that.

00:41:44.950 --> 00:41:47.130
He's really techy and really into it.

00:41:47.130 --> 00:41:49.790
And if anybody knows about it, it's him.

00:41:49.790 --> 00:41:51.830
He's actually, he's a pusher on that one.

00:41:51.830 --> 00:41:52.830
&gt;&gt;Male #2: OK.

00:41:52.830 --> 00:41:53.830
Thank you.

00:41:53.830 --> 00:41:56.370
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: And I think that concept
of 360 degree media is really taking hold

00:41:56.370 --> 00:42:02.191
because both in television, so I know you've
directed "Glee" and "Modern Family" and a

00:42:02.191 --> 00:42:04.230
lot of those experiences were like heroes.

00:42:04.230 --> 00:42:05.650
They existed outside of the film.

00:42:05.650 --> 00:42:08.440
So, you actually go to the website or you
go and experience something that's part of

00:42:08.440 --> 00:42:11.790
the story line that's actually not just in
television.

00:42:11.790 --> 00:42:13.500
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: I think that's fantastic.

00:42:13.500 --> 00:42:17.060
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: You can look into the journey
of a film more and more because can give updates

00:42:17.060 --> 00:42:19.800
from the set and really for fans to just participate
more.

00:42:19.800 --> 00:42:20.800
It's so much easier.

00:42:20.800 --> 00:42:21.850
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: Yeah.

00:42:21.850 --> 00:42:25.441
During the whole making of the movie, I was
doing the, I was trying to keep it as alive

00:42:25.441 --> 00:42:30.110
possible--tweeting a lot of pictures, doing
as much as I could.

00:42:30.110 --> 00:42:38.220
But we didn't do any live streaming stuff
because out of context, this movie could feel

00:42:38.220 --> 00:42:39.220
weird.

00:42:39.220 --> 00:42:40.220
Do you know what I mean?

00:42:40.220 --> 00:42:41.220
It looks a little odd.

00:42:41.220 --> 00:42:44.870
I mean, I think that audiences for this movie
aren't exactly gonna know what they're in

00:42:44.870 --> 00:42:51.870
for when they go in because it is an unusual
hybrid of a movie.

00:42:51.870 --> 00:42:56.030
And it's hard to express the tone of the movie
in the advertising.

00:42:56.030 --> 00:42:57.410
Do you know what I'm saying?

00:42:57.410 --> 00:42:58.410
Kind of?

00:42:58.410 --> 00:42:59.410
Weird?

00:42:59.410 --> 00:43:01.990
Like, you don't really, I'm just assuming
from your reaction that it was better than

00:43:01.990 --> 00:43:03.600
you thought it was gonna be.

00:43:03.600 --> 00:43:05.630
So, which I'm happy to take.

00:43:05.630 --> 00:43:06.630
[laughter]

00:43:06.630 --> 00:43:07.630
By the way.

00:43:07.630 --> 00:43:09.160
So, that's all good.

00:43:09.160 --> 00:43:10.900
And that creates word of mouth.

00:43:10.900 --> 00:43:13.920
I'd rather have a low expectation with a high
result, you know?

00:43:13.920 --> 00:43:17.270
&gt;&gt;Male Presenter: Well, I think that because
it has such a frame of reference that everybody--.

00:43:17.270 --> 00:43:20.980
You hear the songs and you automatically remember
and associate with those.

00:43:20.980 --> 00:43:23.930
And that brings both good stuff and possible
baggage, so yeah.

00:43:23.930 --> 00:43:24.950
I think that's good.

00:43:24.950 --> 00:43:25.950
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: Yeah.

00:43:25.950 --> 00:43:27.020
And the same with cast members.

00:43:27.020 --> 00:43:28.020
&gt;&gt;Female #2: Hi.

00:43:28.020 --> 00:43:29.020
Thanks for coming, by the way.

00:43:29.020 --> 00:43:30.020
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: My pleasure.

00:43:30.020 --> 00:43:31.020
&gt;&gt;Female #2: Yeah.

00:43:31.020 --> 00:43:32.020
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: I'm loving this, by the way.

00:43:32.020 --> 00:43:33.020
This is fun for me.

00:43:33.020 --> 00:43:34.370
&gt;&gt;Female #2: Comment.

00:43:34.370 --> 00:43:37.930
The school prom choreography in "She's All
That" was the best thing that ever happened

00:43:37.930 --> 00:43:39.000
to me in sixth grade.

00:43:39.000 --> 00:43:40.000
So, it was awesome.

00:43:40.000 --> 00:43:41.140
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: That was me.

00:43:41.140 --> 00:43:42.140
[laughter]

00:43:42.140 --> 00:43:43.770
&gt;&gt;Female #2: Thank you for that.

00:43:43.770 --> 00:43:45.400
[laughs] I love it.

00:43:45.400 --> 00:43:46.620
I love it.

00:43:46.620 --> 00:43:48.640
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: Yep, yep, yep.

00:43:48.640 --> 00:43:50.810
I had about two hours to put that whole thing
together.

00:43:50.810 --> 00:43:51.810
And I'm not kidding.

00:43:51.810 --> 00:43:55.020
That was actually, they literally brought
in the dancers.

00:43:55.020 --> 00:43:59.000
I taught them it in two hours in the lobby.

00:43:59.000 --> 00:44:05.130
It was the Cerritos Auto Square where we shot
that in like, Long Beach.

00:44:05.130 --> 00:44:08.900
And the next day, we were literally shooting
it all day.

00:44:08.900 --> 00:44:10.150
It was the craziest thing.

00:44:10.150 --> 00:44:11.520
I was just like, "Hollywood."

00:44:11.520 --> 00:44:12.620
&gt;&gt;Female #2: Good times.

00:44:12.620 --> 00:44:13.620
Yeah.

00:44:13.620 --> 00:44:18.350
But my question is, Nicholas Sparks came a
few weeks ago promoting "The Lucky One."

00:44:18.350 --> 00:44:19.350
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: Uh-huh.

00:44:19.350 --> 00:44:21.850
&gt;&gt;Female #2: And I know he wrote "A Walk to
Remember."

00:44:21.850 --> 00:44:22.850
I was wondering--.

00:44:22.850 --> 00:44:23.850
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: I have that song.

00:44:23.850 --> 00:44:24.850
I have two of them.

00:44:24.850 --> 00:44:25.850
&gt;&gt;Female #2: Definitely.

00:44:25.850 --> 00:44:30.310
So, I was wondering, what's the dynamics between
working with authors in movies that are adapted

00:44:30.310 --> 00:44:31.310
from novels?

00:44:31.310 --> 00:44:34.480
Like, what's that dynamic with working with
those authors as a director and things like

00:44:34.480 --> 00:44:35.480
that?

00:44:35.480 --> 00:44:36.480
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: Well, I can only speak to
mine.

00:44:36.480 --> 00:44:37.480
&gt;&gt;Female #2: Yeah.

00:44:37.480 --> 00:44:40.050
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: To my experiences, which
is during "Walk to Remember," that was, I

00:44:40.050 --> 00:44:46.420
was very, very, it was very precarious because
I was changing the whole time period of the

00:44:46.420 --> 00:44:48.220
movie and it was about his sister.

00:44:48.220 --> 00:44:51.600
So, I was very nervous about how he was going
to react.

00:44:51.600 --> 00:44:56.170
&gt;&gt;Female #2: 'Cause it was originally set
in the '40s.

00:44:56.170 --> 00:44:57.540
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: Yes.

00:44:57.540 --> 00:44:58.540
Yeah.

00:44:58.540 --> 00:45:03.290
And so, what I made sure what I did--and I
did this actually with John Waters in "Hairspray"

00:45:03.290 --> 00:45:08.380
and I'm doing it right now with Jonathan Tropper
on "This is Where I Leave You"--I have unending

00:45:08.380 --> 00:45:11.200
conversations with them where I really keep
them in the loop.

00:45:11.200 --> 00:45:15.041
And they feel really appreciated and part
of the process.

00:45:15.041 --> 00:45:19.250
And I don't make any dramatic move without
talking to them.

00:45:19.250 --> 00:45:23.970
And it's not like what they say is gonna influence
me a lot because I have the story as I see

00:45:23.970 --> 00:45:26.130
it in my head.

00:45:26.130 --> 00:45:28.480
And once again, that's the only frame of reference
I can do it from.

00:45:28.480 --> 00:45:35.300
If I try to live in somebody else's box, it
just won't work.

00:45:35.300 --> 00:45:39.900
So, I just have Nick really close.

00:45:39.900 --> 00:45:44.460
I kept, and then "Last Song," I don't know
if you know the lore behind this, but this

00:45:44.460 --> 00:45:45.810
was crazy.

00:45:45.810 --> 00:45:48.730
And this is so pure Nick.

00:45:48.730 --> 00:45:50.540
That Nick.

00:45:50.540 --> 00:45:52.360
[laughter]

00:45:52.360 --> 00:45:58.590
That my, we got a call from Disney saying
Miley Cyrus, her favorite movie is "Walk to

00:45:58.590 --> 00:45:59.590
Remember."

00:45:59.590 --> 00:46:00.720
And she wants to do a movie like that.

00:46:00.720 --> 00:46:01.720
"Do you have anything?

00:46:01.720 --> 00:46:02.720
Can you come up with something?"

00:46:02.720 --> 00:46:05.650
And my sister said, "Let me think."

00:46:05.650 --> 00:46:07.070
And she literally had the nerve.

00:46:07.070 --> 00:46:14.750
She called Nicholas Sparks and he took her
call and she said, "Do you have anything you

00:46:14.750 --> 00:46:16.270
could dust off?

00:46:16.270 --> 00:46:18.450
Anything in your drawer that might--?"

00:46:18.450 --> 00:46:25.400
He's like, "No, but I've been thinking that
my next book should be for young audiences

00:46:25.400 --> 00:46:26.400
again.

00:46:26.400 --> 00:46:29.090
So, let me think about this."

00:46:29.090 --> 00:46:32.140
And he called her back the next day and he
said, "I have it.

00:46:32.140 --> 00:46:33.140
Here's what it is.

00:46:33.140 --> 00:46:35.450
And I'm gonna write the book and the script
at the same time."

00:46:35.450 --> 00:46:36.450
&gt;&gt;Female #2: Thanks.

00:46:36.450 --> 00:46:37.450
Wow.

00:46:37.450 --> 00:46:38.590
&gt;&gt;Adam Shankman: "And I'm writing it for her.

00:46:38.590 --> 00:46:44.160
And I'll release the book right in time for
it to precede the opening of the movie."

00:46:44.160 --> 00:46:45.530
